[{'author_name': 'Lee Cherry', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/109530340715657378099/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-msFMJKW9Saw/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAACk/NJ8b6Z6SeiE/s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4/photo.jpg', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a year ago', 'text': 'Immaculate apartment with original furnishings from a wealthy Danish family dating back to 1890. 

Two sisters lived there until their deaths and donated their apartment to the National museum. As they were unmarried, nothing in the apartment was updated after their father passed away in 1890. They were one of the first houses in Denmark to get electricity and running water. They even had one of the first telephones; family had 1 digit phone number - 7 - showing their prominence in the country. 

Everything is preserved perfectly and allows for a glimpse into how life was lived over 100 years ago. 

Available as a guided tour only, as apartment is protected by the state. 

Guided tour is free with Copenhagen card from National Museum. Can redeem in lieu of free gift.', 'time': 1467582135}, {'author_name': 'Dan Thorup', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/101492900481009760313/reviews', 'language': 'da', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-Sa5_8_65sBA/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAK48/GBxVfnny5pc/s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba6/photo.jpg', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': 'a month ago', 'text': 'Utrolig historisk og spændende oplevelse. Lejligheden er fra slutningen af 1800 tallet og indretningen er stadig helt den samme. Meget fascinerende. Rundvisningen tager en lille time og man hører både om familien og livet den gang. I literally felt as if I were in a fairy tale. The park was ABSOLUTELY beautiful. Light show at the end of the night was the perfect way to end a perfect day. Nice ride selection.. Great food options.', 'time': 1527714581}, {'author_name': 'Anwarul Quadir', 'author_url': 'https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/111190060217065145383/reviews', 'language': 'en', 'profile_photo_url': 'https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-9j8WP97my8k/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAok/02EVMzV48jE/s128-c0x00000000-cc-rp-mo-ba4/photo.jpg', 'rating': 5, 'relative_time_description': '3 weeks ago', 'text': "This is the one of the best places I've been to so far. To some the entry tickets might seem to be expensive but believe me this nothing compared to what you see. It is not just an amusement park but this beautiful Park on itself. It's a great way to spend quality time with the whole family and the children playing around the garden looking at the beautiful flowers beautiful sceneries the waters and nicely decorated ships and amazingly decorated restaurants. Go here early so that you can give it the full day and relax around having lunch or grabbing some coffee while you sit outside or maybe a drink or two. You have places to store your luggage and there are live concerts and other events going around the park every day.

Overall the place is very well planned for children, handicapped or elderly people but I had some rough experiences using three different cards around the park since some were working and some card readers were not working. I specially had trouble using it in the luggage storage area. So this meant that I had to take help from the staff that were available and they were very friendly and they try to help me out but I had hard time changing currencies. But all of this doesn't feel much because the park was so pretty, beautiful and well maintained

In the end I would like to thank the park authorities (great job you inspire us to raise our standards) and the Danish government for setting-up such an amazing garden which is amazing and gives positive energy in our lives.", 'time': 1526043346}]

Lovely building and space too. We went round the French art ~1800-1950, spread over three floors. The collection is remarkable, with all the big names (Monet, Degas, Renoir, Gaugain, Renoir, and even some Rousseau that were remarkably different from the 'primitive' paintings he is famous for). First room had some of the more modern artists (Miro, Man Ray), but most of it was older than that (a dozen or so other rooms).\n\nIt was a little frustrating not to have an audio guide or even labels with comments by the paintings. But I believe that was a deliberate decision on the part of the curator to create a space focused on the art, and the bold colours on the walls is quite striking. About 2hrs to go round.
